> [!wikipedia]+ [Wikipedia](<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maryland_Campaign>)
> <iframe width="100%" height="1000" frameBorder="0" src="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maryland_Campaign"></iframe>

> [!summary]- Summary
> The **[[Maryland Campaign]]** (September 1862) was a critical Confederate military operation during the **[[American Civil War]]**, led by General **[[Robert E. Lee]]**. It marked the first Confederate invasion of the North and aimed to influence foreign recognition, gather supplies, and sway Maryland to join the Confederacy. The campaign culminated in the **[[Battle of Antietam]]**, the bloodiest single-day battle in U.S. history, which led to a tactical stalemate but a strategic Union victory. President **[[Abraham Lincoln]]** used this opportunity to issue the preliminary **[[Emancipation Proclamation]]**.

> [!chronology]+ Chronology
>
> | Year  | Event                             | Description                                                                                              |
> |-------|-----------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
> | 1862  | **[[Robert E. Lee]] Crosses the Potomac** | Lee leads the Army of Northern Virginia across the Potomac River, beginning the Maryland Campaign.         |
> | 1862  | **Special Order 191 Lost**        | Lee's orders outlining his campaign strategy are lost and later discovered by Union forces.               |
> | 1862  | **[[Battle of South Mountain]]**  | Union forces engage Confederate troops, delaying their advance.                                           |
> | 1862  | **[[Battle of Harpers Ferry]]**   | Confederate forces capture the Union garrison at Harpers Ferry, securing a key supply point.              |
> | 1862  | **[[Battle of Antietam]]**        | The campaign culminates in this battle, resulting in the bloodiest single day in American history.        |
> | 1862  | **Lee Retreats to Virginia**      | After the battle, Lee's forces withdraw, ending the campaign without achieving their strategic goals.     |

> [!trivia]+ Trivia
> **Interesting Fact**  
> During the Maryland Campaign, General Lee divided his forces into smaller units, a risky strategy that was exposed when Special Order 191 was lost and discovered by Union troops.

> [!quote]+ Quote
> "If I save this army now, I tell you plainly that I owe no thanks to you or to any other person in Washington. You have done your best to sacrifice this army."  
> — **George B. McClellan**, addressing his frustrations with Union leadership after the Maryland Campaign.

